Effect of recall on distribution of distances.

Author

Thelma Panaïotis

Let’s use the agent-based model positions that are representative of plankton position and arbitrary remove some points to simulate lower recall, recompute distances and check if they are representative of overall distances.

#|cache: false
source("utils.R")

Load data

# Null dataset
load("data/04b.null_ks.Rdata")

# Simulation results
sim_res <- read_parquet("data/12b.simulation_results.parquet")

# Get only simulation results of the best model
sim_dist <- sim_res %>% 
  filter(d_length == 50 & h == 200000) %>%# best parameters
  #filter(when == "after") %>% # keep only distances after displacement (~plankton distances)
  select(img_name, p1, p2, when, dist)

Points recall and distance recall

Extract all points from distances.

points <- sim_dist %>% 
  select(img_name, p1, p2) %>% 
  pivot_longer(p1:p2, values_to = "point", names_to = NULL) %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  arrange(img_name, point)
Note

The recall value should be applied to points and not distances.

For each recall value:

  • drop points (randomly)

  • get distances between remaining points

# Recall values to try
recall_values <- seq(0.1, 1, by = 0.1)

rec_val <- recall_values[1]

# Loop over recall values
bar <- lapply(recall_values, function(rec_val) {
  print(rec_val)  
  
  # Subsample points (i.e. apply recall)
  points_sub <- points %>% 
    slice_sample(prop = rec_val) %>% 
    arrange(img_name, point)
  
  # Get all combinations of remaining points
  cross_sub <- points_sub %>% 
    rename(p1 = point) %>% 
    mutate(p2 = p1) %>% 
    group_by(img_name) %>% 
    expand(p1, p2) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    filter(p1 != p2)
  
  # Let’s find distances between these points
  dist_sub_before <- cross_sub %>% 
    left_join(sim_dist %>% filter(when == "before"), by = join_by(img_name, p1, p2)) %>% 
    drop_na(dist) %>% 
    mutate(rec_val = rec_val)
  dist_sub_after <- cross_sub %>% 
    left_join(sim_dist %>% filter(when == "after"), by = join_by(img_name, p1, p2)) %>% 
    drop_na(dist) %>% 
    mutate(rec_val = rec_val)
  
  # Bind together
  dist_sub <- bind_rows(dist_sub_before, dist_sub_after)
  
  return(dist_sub)
}) %>% 
  bind_rows()

Let’s check how the distance recall varies with points recall.

# Compute number and proportion of retained distances
baz <- bar %>% 
  count(rec_val, name = "n_dist") %>% 
  mutate(prop_dist = n_dist / max(n_dist))

ggplot(baz) +
  geom_path(aes(x = rec_val, y = prop_dist)) + 
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, colour = "grey") +
  xlim(0, 1) + ylim(0, 1) +
  labs(x = "Points recall", y = "Distance recall") +
  ggtitle("Distances recall VS points recall") +
  theme_classic()

This means that if point recall is 0.5, distance recall is ~0.25.

Kuiper statistic VS number of distances for various recall values

Now, let’s compute Kuiper stat between plankton (i.e. after) and null (i.e. before) distances for each recall value.

For each recall value:

  • compute 10000-quantiles if needed

  • compute Kuiper stat between plankton and null distances

rec_val <- recall_values[1]
recall_ks <- lapply(recall_values, function(rec_val) {
  # Get distances for this recall value
  bar_rec <- bar %>% filter(rec_val == !!rec_val)
  
  # Extract distances before and after
  dist_before <- bar_rec %>% filter(when == "before") %>% pull(dist)
  dist_after <- bar_rec %>% filter(when == "after") %>% pull(dist)
  
  # Number of distances
  n_dist_before <- length(dist_before)
  n_dist_after <- length(dist_after)
  
  # Extract 10000-quantiles if needed
  if (n_dist_before > 10000) {
    dist_before <- quantile(dist_before, probs = probs, names = FALSE)
  }
  if (n_dist_after > 10000) {
    dist_after <- quantile(dist_after, probs = probs, names = FALSE)
  }
  
  # Compute Kuiper statistic
  ks <- kuiper_stat(dist_before, dist_after)
  
  # Return results
  res <- tibble(
    rec_val = rec_val,
    n_dist_before = n_dist_before,
    n_dist_after = n_dist_after,
    n_dist = (n_dist_before + n_dist_after) / 2,
    kuiper_stat = ks,
    dist_before_qt = list(dist_before),
    dist_after_qt = list(dist_after)
  )
  
  return(res)
  
}) %>% 
  bind_rows()

recall_ks <- recall_ks %>% 
  mutate(
    log_n_dist = log10(n_dist),
    log_kuiper_stat = log10(kuiper_stat)
  )

Plot Kuiper statistic VS number of distances.

ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(data = null_ks_n_dist, aes(x = log_n_dist, y = log_kuiper_stat, group = log_n_dist), colour = "gray", outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_polygon(data = null_ks_rib, aes(x = log_n_dist, y = y), alpha = 0.1) +
  geom_point(data = recall_ks, aes(x = log_n_dist, y = log_kuiper_stat, colour = rec_val)) +
  labs(x = "N distances", y = "Kuiper statistic", colour = "Points\nrecall") +
  scale_colour_viridis_c() +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = label_math(expr = 10^.x, format = force), breaks = seq(2, 8, by = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_math(expr = 10^.x, format = force)) +
  theme_classic()
Note

When the recall decreases, it becomes impossible to distinguish between after (plankton) and before (null) distances, but overall this depends on the number of distances.

Important

Should we:

  • increase the number of images in the simulation? This is costly in terms of computation.

  • do the recall experiment from observation data? Observation data already has a recall lower than 1.
